[{"id":"db362b69e96e953e271bc9d445f9c346","from":"John Amerling","from_email":"john_amerling@earthlink.net","to":"J. Epstein","to_list":[{"name":"J. Epstein","email":"jeeproject@yahoo.com"}],"cc_list":[],"subject":"FW:","date":"2008-03-05T16:09:48.000Z","formatted_date":"Mar 5, 2008","formatted_time":"4:09 PM","body":"FYI\n\n \n\nFrom: John Amerling [mailto:john_amerling@earthlink.net] \nSent: Wednesday, March 05, 2008 10:43 AM\nTo: Darren Indyke\nSubject: \n\n \n\nI just pulled an article from the internet and it does a far better job than\nI could in summarizing the meeting. My short take on it was:\n\n \n\n1.       The applicant came into the meeting trying to emphasize that the\nproposal was backed by local persons, as opposed to off island continentals,\nwho ought to be supported.\n\n2.       The proposal, they said orally, was not to build and operate a\nreplica of the Willy T as depicted in their written application; instead the\nproject was an ecologically driven effort to provide moorings to save the\nocean floor and educate children and the only way to pay to install and\nmaintain them was to use revenues generated by the restaurant.\n\n3.       The audience and even the Commission seemed skeptical about this\npolitically correct spin.\n\n4.       Note that the snake oil salesman employed by the applicant was\nMarshall Bell. \n\n5.       The Commission has 30 days to make a decision.\n\n \n\nI will send the article in a separate e mail.  \n\n \n\nLafayette Contractors, LLC\n\n6100 Red Hook Quarters, Suite A2-7\n\nSt. Thomas, VI 00802\n\n340 779-8054 (O)\n\n340 779-8055 (FAX)\n\n340 690-7194 (Cell)\n\n \n\n","body_html":"<html xmlns:v=\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:vml\" xmlns:o=\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office\" xmlns:w=\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:word\" xmlns:m=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/2004/12/omml\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40\">\n\n<head>\n<META HTTP-EQUIV=\"Content-Type\" CONTENT=\"text/html; charset=us-ascii\">\n<